                                    <p><q>The stone leans markedly to the north-west: the current height of the stone (i.e. vertical drop from top to the ground surface) is 1.9m, however, if the stone were fully vertical, its height would be c. 2.3m</q> (<!--<ref source="https://maps.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=???">-->Archaeological Survey of Ireland (ASI) field report<!--</ref>-->).</p>
                                </support>
                                <condition>The stone is weathered and largely lichen-covered. The middle section of the south-west face presents a smooth, almost polished surface, probably the result of farm stock using this side of the stone as a scratching post; part of the inscription may have been obliterated here.</condition>
